 and the Conch reminds every mouth that silence can be a bridge and not a blade. The Temple’s blue light will mark each oath, and the lamps will not flinch if we tell them nothing we fear to keep; that is the only kind of promise the city deserves. I propose a rhythm: Blue Fist safety captains on every pier with drum-codes that freeze lifts in a breath and pull people clear before a horn can rattle bones, and Tidewardens on-call to safeguard those freezes so no opportunist turns safety into theft. Seizures should ring with cause and not whim, logged to a bell-and-drum tally that both sides can read by touch if the fog eats sight, with three strikes against any crew that plays games with the code. Let us trade not insults but protocols, not threats but timings; I will hold the Conch and measure each voice until we have a pattern that catches us when tempers slip like wet rope. If we do this under blue, with the sea as witness and the city at our backs, then the night will remember and the day will follow.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Kema Hookhand\", \"lines\": \"A safety captain on every pier is a cost and a pride both, and I will pay both if my people stop hearing horns drill through their sleep like a tax. Drum-codes that halt cranes on a heartbeat without dropping a pallet into someone’s spine are a language I can make my crews learn, and I will beat the rhythm into the boards until the piers themselves remember. No horns at sleeping families, and no seizures that arrive like storms with names, because we are human and not weather. Bring me that fairness and I will keep the hardliners’ fists unclenched, their brass-lamp tucked away like a bad idea that learned shame, and I will walk the line myself to prove it. But hear me clean, Thalen: if the Ledgers masked clerks try to buy this slack with hush-paper and carve a toll into our breath, I will turn this dock into a stage and break a chain for every coin they count; I would rather starve loudly than swallow quiet 