 breath, and you invite both factions to touch the water before they speak as if cooling a thought could save a life. You confess your own fear that hush used badly kills more than noise used badly, and you promise to name that fear aloud every time you raise the shell. You ask that any who object to holy witness say so now, under open sky, rather than mutter later under stone.\", \"outcome\": \"Shunn arrives with quiet feet and a lamp that hums in the old vowel of the harbor, and the bowl catches the pier’s tremor until even the wood seems calmer. Kema gives a small nod like a coin set aside for charity she believes in, and her crew relax in the knowledge that faith can stand with pay without stealing from it. Miren rolls his shoulders once as if he had been carrying a knot alone, and then speaks more slowly, finding words that feel less like orders and more like oaths. A Ledger clerk at the edge of the crowd leaves in a huff when he sees the lamp descend too early for masked convenience, and his absence frees the talk to leave numbers and touch people. You feel a colder current brush your throat scar when you raise the Conch, a reminder of the hush you once misused, and you let that chill guide your mercy rather than your fear. When the truce is sealed, Shunn pours a line of slack water along the chalkboard’s edge and the marks do not run, and everyone watching understands that the tide chose to be gentle because you did first.\"},\n        {\"id\": \"C4\", \"title\": \"Lean on Tidewarden Authority\", \"text\": \"You invite Commodore Jath Pell to stand at the far edge of the pier with his horn-crew visible but silent, a tall shadow of consequence arranged where everyone can see it blink. You say plainly that there will be no brass flares today, not because fear forbids them but because wisdom has found a faster light. You tell Kema that a strike that burns the lamp will burn her bargaining table with it, and you tell Miren that seizures flung like nets catch too m